    skos:definition """
    <p>
    Collection of nine soil surface samples to 3 cm in differing microhabitats (collected immediately before the Soil sub-site characterisation protocol samples are collected), or microhabitat of a target species/taxa/group.
    This module serves as a sub-protocol of the <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/6fd9d31f-9a77-4fc1-9eee-23ea8af32b95">Soil</a> module. 
    Prior to implementing this protocol, it is essential to thoroughly review the Introduction, Key Definitions and Terminology,
    Rationale, and Module Overview provided in the "<a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/6fd9d31f-9a77-4fc1-9eee-23ea8af32b95">Soil</a>" module.
    These sections will provide you with important contextual information and a comprehensive understanding of the protocol.
    </p>
    """^^rdf:HTML ;
    skos:note """
    <h3 id="additional-guidelines">Additional guidelines</h3>
<h4 id="aligning-with-soil-sample-sub-sites">
  A. Aligning with soil sample sub-sites
</h4>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      If undertaking the <em><a href="https://linkeddata.tern.org.au/viewers/dawe-vocabs?uri=https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/e3ad3e5b-7c1c-4b59-bdb1-297f707d2ca3">Soil sub-site samples</a></em> protocol, the
      metagenomic samples can be collected from the same locations immediately
      before the soil sub-site samples are collected.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
<h4 id="mixed-silica-granules">B. Mixed silica granules</h4>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      Read
      <a
        href="https://www.silicageldirect.com.au/content/SilicaGelBluefinal.pdf"
        ><u>material safety data sheet</u></a
      >
      before handling silica.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Prefill 9 zip lock bags per plot with ½ a cup of mixed silica granules
      prior to the survey. Prepare a safe, well ventilated working area and use
      the required PPE.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      More mixed silica granules than ½ a cup per zip lock bag may be required
      for damp samples.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Silica will need to be checked regularly and changed until the
      self-indicating granules retain their original colour.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Store spare silica away from food or beverages in tightly closed
      containers in a cool, dry and well-ventilated area.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      A change in colour (usually after 2–3 days) of the self-indicating
      granules reveals that the moisture absorbing capacity of the mix has been
      reached and it needs to be replaced with fresh silica.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      To replace silica, prepare a safe, well ventilated working area. Using the
      required PPE, empty spent silica into a suitably sized empty airtight
      receptacle (e.g. 20 L bucket with lid).
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Replace ½ a cup of mixed silica granules into relevant zip lock bags and
      reseal.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Do not discard the spent silica. It can be reactivated by drying in an
      oven at 110°C for 2 hours or until the indicator colour reverts. Ovens
      used for food preparation are not suitable for this process and PPE
      recommendations should be followed at all times when handling silica.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
    """^^rdf:HTML ;
